## Economic Foundations and Impact of Slavery

Slavery was the economic engine of the American South, underpinning the production of lucrative cash crops that fueled both regional and national prosperity.

### The Rise of Cotton and the "Cotton Kingdom"

The invention of the cotton gin in 1793 dramatically increased cotton harvesting productivity, leading to a surge in cotton production and exports. By the mid-19th century, cotton accounted for half of all U.S. exports, solidifying the South’s global economic position ([HISTORY, 2018](https://www.history.com/articles/slavery-profitable-southern-economy); [American Yawp, 2025](https://www.americanyawp.com/text/11-the-cotton-revolution/)).

The expansion of cotton cultivation led to the growth of the "Cotton Belt" and the "Black Belt," regions characterized by fertile soil and high concentrations of enslaved laborers. Cotton and slavery became so intertwined that they defined the Southern economy and social identity ([American Yawp, 2025](https://www.americanyawp.com/text/11-the-cotton-revolution/)).

### Profitability and Wealth Generation

Slavery generated immense wealth for Southern planters and created more millionaires per capita in the Mississippi River valley than anywhere else in the nation by the Civil War’s outset. The Confederacy, had it been a separate nation, would have ranked as the fourth richest globally, largely due to its slave-based economy ([HISTORY, 2018](https://www.history.com/articles/slavery-profitable-southern-economy)).

### Broader Economic Roles

Beyond agriculture, enslaved people worked in domestic service, transportation, manufacturing, and food processing in urban areas, contributing to a diverse economic base in the South ([Encyclopedia.com, 2025](https://www.encyclopedia.com/humanities/applied-and-social-sciences-magazines/economic-impact-slavery-south)).

